<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="dd931c20-acc7-594e-8593-2bab3aa09165" activityNameId="e6fe4a91-80d8-4fb1-a9a0-32fed0baa7a2" parentActivityId="a18c8325-1f88-4510-81ab-c91a2802e72e" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1" energyValues="0">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">n-olefins production</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">From the reception n-paraffins or ethylene at the factory gate.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with 1 kg of n-olefins 100% af the factory gate. The dataset includes the input materials, energy uses, transport, infrastructure, water consumption, production of waste for inceneration, air and water emissions.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the production of 1 kg of n-olefins from a combination of two processes: n-paraffins dehydrogenation and ethylene oligomerization. It is assumed that both processes have a similar yield. The relation n-paraffins to ethylene is of 35% to 65%. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The data are for European production. Materials and energy inputs are from literature sources or estimation based on literature sources. Infrastructure and water consumption are estimated from a large chemical plant. Transportation is the result of a calculation based on literature sources. Emission to air and water are from literature sources. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">[This dataset was already contained in the ecoinvent database version 2. It was not individually updated during the transfer to ecoinvent version 3. Life Cycle Impact Assessment results may still have changed, as they are affected by changes in the supply chain, i.e. in other datasets. This dataset was generated following the ecoinvent quality guidelines for version 2. It may have been subject to central changes described in the ecoinvent version 3 change report (http://www.ecoinvent.org/database/ecoinvent-version-3/reports-of-changes/), and the results of the central updates were reviewed extensively. The changes added e.g. consistent water flows and other information throughout the database. The documentation of this dataset can be found in the ecoinvent reports of version 2, which are still available via the ecoinvent website. The change report linked above covers all central changes that were made during the conversion process.]</text>
        </generalComment>
        <tag>ConvertedDataset</tag>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <classification classificationId="7ac1cbc6-1385-4a68-8647-ed7aa78db201">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">EcoSpold01Categories</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">chemicals/organics</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Data based on the European n-olefins production</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">n-Olefins in the context of the detergents production means higher (C10 to C16) olefins, produced either by dehydrogenation of the corresponding n-paraffins or by ethylene oligomerization. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Dehydrogenation of n-paraffins: a combination of two processes – Pacol (paraffin catalyst olefin) and Olex (olefin extraction) – is most often used. The first step, at a temperature of 450 to 510°C and a pressure of 0.3 Mpa, uses a hydrogen : carbon ratio of 9:1. The whole process uses a platinum catalyst (0.8 wt%) on alumina, activated by adding lithium, arsenic or germanium. The resulting paraffin-olefin mixture is then separated in the second process, using molecular sieves, absorbing olefins more strongely.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3"></text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Ethylene oligomerization: Two different methods are mainly used for the production of n-olefins out of ethylene: the SHOP (Shell’s higher olefin process) or the Ziegler reaction.  </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">For the dataset it is assumed based on literature sources that both ways have a similar yield and the relation n-paraffins to ethylene for the synthesis of n-olefins is of 35% to 65%. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Behr (2000)</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="1995-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">data of published literature</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="9ecd92f5-68fa-55e0-948c-cb085bef5f42" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" amount="1.0" sourceId="e297d3d2-9e5e-468a-8f47-83e92aa0aa23" sourceYear="2000" sourceFirstAuthor="Behr A." intermediateExchangeId="0e99b6e3-a3e1-47a2-8fb5-5ced89ddd778" productionVolumeAmount="1.32236940655721">
        <name xml:lang="en">n-olefins</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Olefins is a common name for all aliphatic hydrocarbons that contain at least one carbon-carbon double bond - e.g. ethene, propene or isopropene. The name olefin signifies oil-forming gas: these substances have the property to form oily liquids when reacting with halogens. n-Olefins in the context of the detergents production means higher (C10 to C16) olefins, produced either by dehydrogenation of the corresponding n-paraffins or by ethylene oligomerization.
EcoSpold01Location=RER</comment>
        <property propertyId="f2283db2-62e4-467f-b9ac-c4f45be563b4" amount="0.876404494382023" isDefiningValue="false" isCalculatedAmount="false" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7">
